snippet.textDisplay: I love Kenny Rogers song about You gotta know when to hold'em, when to fold'em, when to walk, or run away.  I use that "formula" when I am campaigning my dog in competition obedience when I see an exercise is "broken" in a trial with no opportunity to fix the problem before the next obedience trial if that trial is held the same weekend. You actually save more money than you lose by packing up and going home, and save more hours in remedial training than you lose by letting the dog repeat the mistake in an arena where you cannot give a second command without failing the class.  I've done that with a past Sheltie that eventually finished her obedience trial champion title (OTCH), and faced a five hour trip home after she did a short go out, requiring a second command to continue to the sit point for the directed jumping exercise. At the time, I did not know the club (one in the Des Moines, IA) area did not use baby gates and stanchions for a go out target.  Hard lesson learned for me as a trainer learning with my first serious obedience trial dog.  But then again, in this "game," you have to know when to hold'em, (keep showing), or when to fold'em, walk, or run, OR drive away, or drive five hours in my case, to return to the "drawing board," train, then try again so we can "hold'em" the next time. AND I love Dolly Parton, and her other best friend, Reba McIntyre.
